{
  "slug": "negation",
  "title": "Negation: nicht & kein",
  "level": "A1",
  "explainer_md": "German has two ways to say \"not\" — and a simple rule decides which one to use.\n\n**kein** negates **nouns** that have *ein* or no article at all. It takes the same endings as *ein*:\n\n*Ich habe **ein** [[Auto]].* → *Ich habe **kein** Auto.* — I don't have a car.\n\n*Sie trinkt [[Kaffee]].* → *Sie trinkt **keinen** Kaffee.* — She doesn't drink (any) coffee.\n\n| | m | f | n | pl |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Nominativ | kein | kein**e** | kein | kein**e** |\n| Akkusativ | kein**en** | kein**e** | kein | kein**e** |\n| Dativ | kein**em** | kein**er** | kein**em** | kein**en** |\n| Genitiv | kein**es** | kein**er** | kein**es** | kein**er** |\n\n*(The Dativ and Genitiv rows are here for reference — those cases come in later topics.)*\n\n**nicht** negates everything else — verbs, adjectives, and nouns with *der/die/das* or a possessive:\n\n*Ich verstehe **nicht**.* — I don't understand.\n\n*Das ist **nicht** gut.* — That is not good.\n\n*Das ist **nicht** mein [[Buch]].* — That is not my book.\n\n**Where does nicht go?** Usually at the end of the sentence — but before adjectives, places and the second part of the verb: *Er kommt heute **nicht**.* · *Das Essen ist **nicht** teuer.*\n\n**Tip:** quick test — could you put *ein* in front of the noun? Then negate with **kein**: *Ich habe (einen) Hund* → *Ich habe keinen Hund*. Everything else gets **nicht**.",
